The '''East African Revival''' ({{lang-lg|Okulokoka}}) was an important [[Christian revival|renewal]] movement within [[Evangelicalism|Protestant Evangelicalism]] in East Africa during the late 1920s and 1930s.<ref>{{cite book|last=Ward|first=Kevin|title=The East African Revival:  History and Legacies|year=2012|publisher=Ashgate Publishing|location=Surrey, England|page=3}}</ref> The Revival began at a [[Church Missionary Society]] (CMS) mission station in the Belgian territory of [[Ruanda-Urundi]] in 1929, and spread to [[Uganda Protectorate]], [[Tanganyika Territory]] and [[Kenya Colony]] during the 1930s and 1940s.

The revival contributed to the significant growth of the Church in East Africa in the 1940s through the 1970s and had a visible influence on Western missionaries who were observer-participants of the movement.<ref>{{cite book|last=MacMaster|first=Richard K.|title=A Gentle Wind of God:  The Influence of the East Africa Revival|year=2006|publisher=Herald Press|location=Scottdale, PA|page= }}</ref>{{page needed|date=July 2012}}

