'''Gbandi''' (or Bandi, Bande, Gbande, Gbunde) is an [[ethnic group]] of [[Liberia]]. It is also the language traditionally spoken by these people.

==People==
The population is estimated at 107,000 people; of which many have fled to [[Guinea]] during the [[First Liberian Civil War|Liberian Civil War]]. Gbandi people practice Islam and Christianity, as well as some traditional beliefs.<ref name=Ethnologue>{{cite web |url=http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=bza |title= Bandi: A language of Liberia |work=Languages of the World |publisher=Ethnologue |accessdate=October 17, 2011}}</ref>

==Language==
[[Gbandi language|Gbandi]] is a Southwestern [[Mande language]]. There are six dialects of the language: Tahamba, Wawana, Wulukoha, Hasala, Lukasa, and Hembeh.<ref name=Ethnologue/>

