{|{{Infobox ship begin <!-- warships except submarines --> |infobox caption= <!-- keywords: yes, nodab; or caption text --> |display title= <!-- keywords: none, ital; or article title with markup --> }} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image=File:HMS Grenadier FL13591.jpg |Ship image size=300px |Ship caption= }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header= |Ship country=UK |Ship flag=[[File:Naval Ensign of the United Kingdom.svg|100x35px|Royal Navy Ensign]] |Ship name=HMS ''Grenadier'' |Ship owner= |Ship namesake= |Ship ordered= |Ship builder=[[Cook, Welton & Gemmell]], [[Beverley]] |Ship laid down=13 June 1942 |Ship launched=26 September 1942 |Ship acquired= |Ship commissioned=10 February 1943 |Ship decommissioned= |Ship in service= |Ship out of service= |Ship struck= |Ship reinstated= |Ship honours= |Ship honors= |Ship fate= |Ship status= |Ship notes= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship class=[[Military class trawler|Military class]] [[Admiralty trawler|trawler]] |Ship displacement= |Ship length= |Ship beam= |Ship draught= |Ship draft= |Ship propulsion= |Ship speed= |Ship range= |Ship complement= |Ship sensors= |Ship EW= |Ship armament= |Ship armour= |Ship armor= |Ship aircraft= |Ship aircraft facilities= |Ship notes= }} |}
'''HMS ''Grenadier''''' (Pennant number: T334) was a [[Military class trawler|Military class]] [[Admiralty trawler|trawler]] of the British [[Royal Navy]], which served as an [[Anti Submarine Warfare]] Vessel during the Second World War. The ship was built by [[Cook, Welton & Gemmell]] in Beverley, England. She was laid down on 13 June 1942, launched on 26 September 1942 and finally commissioned on 10 February 1943<!-- ? -->. Her role was to support convoys, and deter attack by German u-boats using depth charges. This class of vessel could be fitted with extra guns, and the Grenadier was reported to have had an extra pair of [[Oerlikon 20 mm cannon|Oerlikon 20mm guns]] and a [[List of World War II British naval radar#Type_290|Type 290]] mast mounted radar.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Wright|first1=Malcolm George|title=British and Commonwealth Warship Camouflage of WWII|pages=125|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=CEauCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA125&dq=HMS+Grenadier+T+334&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjYpqyihrLWAhXHYlAKHVYRB0oQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=HMS%20Grenadier%20T%20334&f=false|accessdate=19 September 2017}}</ref>
Her most notable engagement occurred on 16 March 1945. That morning she was in convoy alongside the steam merchant ''[[Inger Toft]]'', now operating under the [[Ministry of War]] transport, when at 0900 ''Inger Toft'' was struck by a torpedo fired from [[German submarine U-722|German submarine ''U-722'']] and began to quickly sink. The skipper of ''Grenadier'' at the time was A/SkrLt<!-- ? --> Arthur George Day of the [[Royal Navy Reserve]]. It was common practice when under attack, for the skipper to order the crew to take the vessel to full propulsion whilst dropping depth charges, to avoid being hit whilst trying to hunt the culprit [[U-boat]]. A/SkrLt Day realised that the men of ''Inger Toft'' whose vessel had now fallen beneath the water would have little chance of survival if they followed this routine. He ordered his men to turn the vessel into the direction of the sunken vessel. Whilst ultimately risking his vessel and entire crew, they managed to save the entire 30 man crew of ''Inger Toft'' including the master from the freezing waters. For his actions A/SkrLt Arthur George Day was mentioned in dispatches, he received an oak leaf to be worn on his 1939-1945 war medal. Following the war he returned to his pre-war occupation as a skipper operating from the small fishing port of Milford Haven, Pembrokeshire Wales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uboat.net/allies/commanders/5973.html|title=A/Skr.Lt. Arthur George Day of the Royal Navy Reserve (RNR) - Allied Warship Commanders of WWII - uboat.net|website=uboat.net}}</ref>
Once the war ended ''Grenadier'' was first sold to a merchant fishing firm in Grimsby, she was renamed ''Thurinigia'', later in 1947 she was converted for oil burning but by 1966 she was sold for scrap.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/3471.html|title=Inger Toft (British Steam merchant) - Ships hit by German U-boats during WWII - uboat.net|website=uboat.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/6284.html|title=HMS Grenadier (T 334) of the Royal Navy - British ASW Trawler of the Military class - Allied Warships of WWII - uboat.net|website=uboat.net}}</ref>
