{{Reimprove|date=January 2018}} {{Infobox shopping mall | name = Mustafa Centre | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = Mustafa Centre, Sep 06.JPG | image_width = | caption = Main store along Syed Alwi Road | location = Syed Alwi Road, [[Little India, Singapore|Little India]], [[Singapore]] | coordinates = {{Coord|1|18|35|N|103|51|21|E|type:landmark_region:SG|display=inline,title}} | address = 145 Syed Alwi Road, Singapore 207704 | opening_date = April 1995 | closing_date = | developer = | manager = | owner = Mr. Mustaq Ahmad | architect = | number_of_stores = 1 main store and 3 wings | number_of_anchors = None | floor_area = {{convert|400,000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} | floors = 8 | parking = 0 (roadside parking) | publictransit = [[Farrer Park MRT Station|Farrer Park]] | website = {{URL|http://www.mustafa.com.sg/|www.mustafa.com.sg}} | belowstyle = | footnotes = }}
'''Mustafa Centre''' is one of [[Singapore]]'s [[24/7|24-hour]] [[shopping mall]]s on Syed Alwi Road in the cultural district of [[Little India, Singapore|Little India]], within the [[Planning Areas of Singapore|planning area]] of [[Kallang]].<ref name="about_page">{{cite web | url=http://www.mustafa.com.sg/frmAboutUs.aspx | title=About Mustafa | publisher=Mustafa Centre}}</ref> Within a walking distance from [[Farrer Park MRT Station|Farrer Park]] station on the [[North East MRT Line|North East Line]], Mustafa Centre is a retail hub attracting many shoppers with its wide variety of products and services.
In 1971, Mustaq Ahmad; his father, Haji Mohamed Mustafa (1916-2001); and his uncle, Samsuddin, founded '''Mohamed Mustafa and Samsudin Co Pte Ltd''' ('''MMSC'''), and opened a retail store on Campbell Lane in Singapore.<ref name="infopedia"/> It mainly sold ready-made clothing and later expanded to sale of electronic items. In 1985, Mustaq moved his business to the ground floor of Serangoon Plaza.
As his business expanded, Mustaq bought a shophouse on Syed Alwi Road. Subsequently, he bought the neighboring units and decided to build a new shopping mall to house his business.<ref name="infopedia">{{cite web | url=http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_442_2005-02-03.html | title=Mohamed Mustafa and Samsudin Co Pte Ltd | publisher=Singapore Infopedia | date=February 3, 2005 | accessdate=November 13, 2012 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120417041545/http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_442_2005-02-03.html | archivedate=April 17, 2012 | df= }}</ref> The business expanded internationally, to [[Chennai]], in 2000.<ref name="infopedia"/>
Mustafa Centre sold parallel imported cars in 2005 but has since stopped.{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}
==Facilities== Mustafa Centre houses the Mustafa department store, which caters mainly to the budget market. The department store consists of two shopping centres: one retailing [[jewelry]] and [[household appliance]]s and functioning as a [[supermarket]], and the other selling a variety of other products such as [[book]]s, [[DVD]]s, [[watch]]es, [[Consumer electronics|electronic goods]], [[footwear]], [[toys]] and [[clothing]].
Mustafa Centre sells more than 300,000 items and provides many services such as [[Bureau de change|foreign exchange]] and [[travel]] arrangements.<ref name="about_page"></ref> In late 2011, Mustafa Centre opened a new rooftop restaurant named ''Kebabs ‘n Curries'' in its new wing. <ref name="kebabs_curries_article">{{cite web | url=http://www.hungrygowhere.com/dining-guide/critics-reviews/mustafa-rooftop-restaurant-opens-*aid-31dc3e00/ | title=Mustafa rooftop restaurant opens | publisher=HungryGoWhere Singapore | date=October 13, 2011 | accessdate=February 18, 2015}}</ref> The restaurant serves a range of Asian dishes from 5 pm till 2 am daily. <ref name="kebabs_curries_info">{{cite web | url=http://www.hungrygowhere.com/singapore/Kebabs_n_Curries/ | title=Kebabs & Curries, Jalan Besar Reviews | publisher=HungryGoWhere Singapore | accessdate=February 18, 2015}}</ref>
