{{Politics of Burundi}}
The ''' People's Reconciliation Party''' ({{lang-fr|Parti de la Réconciliation des Personnes}}, PRP) is a minor [[political party]] in [[Burundi]].
==History== The party was established in September 1991 and registered on 30 June 1992.<ref name=TL>Tom Lansford (2014) ''Political Handbook of the World 2014'', CQ Press, p215</ref><ref>[http://www.afrique-express.com/afrique/burundi/burundi-partis-politiques.html Les principaux partis politiques du Burundi] Afrique Express</ref> It nominated Pierre-Claver Sendegeya as its candidate for the [[Burundian presidential election, 1993|1993 presidential elections]]. Sendegeya finished third with 1.5% of the vote.<ref name=AED/>
Led by Jean Bosco Yamuremye, it received 1.4% of the vote in the [[Burundian legislative election, 1993|1993 parliamentary elections]], failing to win a seat.<ref name=AED>[http://africanelections.tripod.com/bi.html Elections in Burundi] African Elections Database</ref>
In 1994 its leader Mathias Hitimana was arrested as the government considered the party to have extremist leanings. The arrest led to riots that affected [[Bujumbura]] for three days.<ref name=TL/> In March 1995 the PRP was given a ministerial post, but the party pulled out of the government in December, and Hitimana was arrested again in January 1996.<ref name=TL/>
The party was given a ministerial post in the transitional government in November 2001, but left the government again in July 2002, before returning in 2003. In 2006 party president Déo Niyonzima was arrested for alleged involvement in a coup plot, but was acquitted in January 2007.<ref name=TL/>
==Ideology== The party supports the restoration of the [[List of Kings of Burundi|monarchy]].<ref name=EKE>Ellen K Eggers (2006) ''Historical Dictionary of Burundi'', Scarecrow Press, p125</ref>
