{{Infobox military installation | name = Qortin Redoubt | native_name = Ridott tal-Qortin | location = [[Mellieħa]], [[Malta]] | image = | caption = | map = Qortin Redoubt map.png | image_mapsize = 300px | map_caption = Map of Qortin Redoubt with its modern alterations | type = [[Redoubt]] | coordinates = {{coord|35|59|11.3|N|14|21|5|E|type:landmark|display=inline}} | ownership = [[Government of Malta]] | controlledby = Private tenant | open_to_public = No | built = 1715–1716 | used = | builder = [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of Saint John]] | materials = [[Limestone]] | height = | condition = Partially intact with modern alterations | battles = | events = }}
'''Qortin Redoubt''' ({{lang-mt|Ridott tal-Qortin}}), also known as '''Eskalar Redoubt''' ({{lang-mt|Ridott t'Eskalar}}), is a [[redoubt]] in the limits of [[Mellieħa]], [[Malta]]. It was built by the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of Saint John]] in 1715–1716 as one of a series of coastal fortifications around the Maltese Islands. Today, the redoubt still exists, but it has some modern modifications.
==History== Qortin Redoubt was built in 1715–1716 as part of the first building programme of coastal fortifications in Malta. It was part of a chain of fortifications that defended the northern coast of Malta, which also included [[Aħrax Tower]], several batteries, redoubts and entrenchments. The nearest fortifications to Qortin Redoubt are [[Tal-Bir Redoubt]] to the west and [[Vendôme Battery]] to the east.
The redoubt originally consisted of a pentagonal platform with a low parapet. A rectangular blockhouse was located at the centre of its gorge. It was not armed with any artillery.
Construction of Qortin Redoubt cost around 1239.8.19 scudi.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Debono|first1=Charles|title=Fortifications - Eskalar Redoubt|url=http://www.mellieha.com/places_interest/fortifications/eskalar_redoubt.htm|website=Mellieha.com|accessdate=21 June 2015}}</ref>
==Present day== Today, the pentagonal platform still exists, but the parapet has been removed. The blockhouse has been demolished and a summer residence has been built in its place.
